    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im a site foreman and i need a quick refresher on the mandatory safety checks for residential scaffolding. what are the main things we gotta check on the setup before the crew is allowed to climb it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey there! As a Site Foreman, your job is to ensure the \"scaffolding is safe for the people\" before a single brick is laid or a worker steps on it. You must have a clear, stable, and secure base before anyone climbs.\n\nFirst, the **grounding** is non-negotiable. The base must be solid, level, and capable of supporting the full weight of the structure. If the ground is soft, you need to use a **scaffolding base** or **ground anchors** to prevent the whole thing from sinking.\n\nNext, the **platforms** must be level and securely anchored. You cannot have a platform that is tilted or swaying; it must be rigid and stable. If the platform is unstable, you must re-anchor it before anyone steps on it.\n\nFinally, the **guardrails** and **ladders** must be in place. The guardrails must be at least 1.2 meters high and fully enclosed to prevent falls. If you don't have a ladder, you must use a **scaffolding ladder** or a **ladder with a safety rail**.\n\nRemember, if you see any of these issues, you must stop work immediately.",
